This article discusses the meeting between President Obama and Pope Francis at the White House. They discussed their shared values and commitments on various issues including providing refuge to those forced to flee their countries, ending extreme poverty, ensuring equal opportunities for all, promoting reconciliation, protecting religious freedom, and managing resources sustainably. The President announced several initiatives to commemorate this historic meeting, including increasing the number of refugees admitted into the US, providing aid to Syrians, protecting minority populations in the Middle East, promoting religious freedom internationally, cooperating with Cuba on healthcare in Haiti, and assisting at-risk youth in Central America. The article also highlights the importance of addressing climate change and protecting the environment, with the President's commitment to reducing greenhouse gas emissions and working towards a global climate agreement. The administration is also partnering with religious and community organizations to promote climate resilience and energy efficiency.